Jumping in at 100% I'm probably overestimating confidence in this forecast, as there's still a lot that could go wrong between now and late February, but I'm going to operate from the standpoint that Iran is on track, until otherwise indicated. There are some great links/comments from other forecasters in the last two days:
@Jean-Pierre --> https://www.gjopen.com/comments/comments/54007  Linked to analysis from someone who's more familiar with the topic.
@morrell --> https://www.gjopen.com/comments/comments/53566  Linked to the report released on Dec 2.
@redacted --> https://www.gjopen.com/comments/comments/53548  Linked to a couple of articles that talk about the report.
@Khalid --> https://www.gjopen.com/comments/comments/54142  Linked to a Bloomberg article discussing the report. The kicker for me is the Iranian elections. The people in power (in Iran) who agreed to this deal surely want to reap the benefits of this deal (politically). And for this to happen, they need to make sure that "implementation day" does happen before the election, so that it's something they can celebrate to their people. "Look what we did -- reelect us!" From what I remember reading years ago, sanctions hurt the everyday citizens more than they hurt the politicians, so if Iran can get the sanctions lifted at least a week or two before the elections, they'll have something tangible to point to when campaigning.
